      "lineNbr": 415,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-07-31T20:23:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is kind of confusing. We don\u0027t use it if we successfully decoded the entire image. Let\u0027s say you have a 10 pixel high image (both the frame and the image). If you only decoded the first 3 rows, you\u0027d set this to 3, and then SkCodec (or the client of incrementalDecode()) would zero-initialize the remaining 7 (unless the memory was already zero-initialized).\n\nNow let\u0027s say that the image is still 10 pixels high, but the frame is from row 5 to 9. If you only decoded 3 rows, but you initialized the first 5, you could return 8, and the caller would zero-initialize the final 2. In SkGifCodec, we just zero-initialize all 10 rows ahead of time (as you do here) and return the height of the image, so the caller knows it doesn\u0027t need to do anything. (To match that behavior, I think you\u0027d want to return fPixelBuffer.height()?) That\u0027s wasted work, and it\u0027s possible there\u0027s a better way to do it, but I haven\u0027t investigated it.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 415,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 415,
        "endChar": 78
      },
      "revId": "36facc38703bfce7dcf6e54ba081722571ffb5ec",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
