      },
      "lineNbr": 463,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-07-31T20:23:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "SkFrameInfo (the public-facing API) does not include a frame rect (deliberately).\n\nSkGifCodec does not clip the frame rect in (the internal) SkFrame. It\u0027s used by setAlphaAndRequiredFrame and by the SkCodec subclass. In either case, I don\u0027t think that clipping early would hurt anything, but if you\u0027re clipping later (i.e. in onIncrementalDecode), it\u0027s not necessary. That said, I\u0027d support adding a comment to SkFrame describing how it\u0027s expected to be used.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 461,
        "startChar": 56,
        "endLine": 463,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "36facc38703bfce7dcf6e54ba081722571ffb5ec",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6e092306_57be412b",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsGifCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 463,
      "author": {
        "id": 8223
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-15T03:51:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This concern about clipping is obsolete. Wuffs now always clips any returned frame rect to the image rect. (If the underlying GIF image has an overhanging frame, those excess pixels will be decoded but written to /dev/null).",
      "parentUuid": "9b9d8a79_cfc55692",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 461,
        "startChar": 56,
        "endLine": 463,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "36facc38703bfce7dcf6e54ba081722571ffb5ec",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "28d7fff0_78fd8925",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsGifCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 463,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-25T19:52:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Just curious - what inspired that change? I thought your intent was to keep Wuffs flexible, since different decoders/browsers have chosen different policies.\n\nhttps://github.com/google/wuffs/blob/master/test/data/artificial/gif-frame-out-of-bounds.gif.make-artificial.txt",
      "parentUuid": "6e092306_57be412b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 461,
        "startChar": 56,
        "endLine": 463,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "36facc38703bfce7dcf6e54ba081722571ffb5ec",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c326e612_af3bfe65",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsGifCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 463,
      "author": {
        "id": 8223
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-26T03:54:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Sorry for the confusion. The intent was never to keep Wuffs flexible. Different decoders have chosen different policies, but Wuffs chooses one particular policy: what Chromium does. The difference between then and now is whether the Wuffs caller (program) or callee (library) is responsible for clipping. Before, it was caller. Now, it is callee.",
      "parentUuid": "28d7fff0_78fd8925",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 461,
        "startChar": 56,
        "endLine": 463,
        "endChar": 51
      },
